    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-12-09T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-12-09T09:00:00-05:00" n="241"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d241">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">438.00/360: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The High Commissioner in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Russell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-12-09T09:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 9, 1925—9 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 10—9:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>76. Referring to my telegram No. 74 of December 5, 4 p.m.<note n="35"
                        xml:id="d241fn35">Not printed.</note> Minister of Foreign Affairs states
                    that French-Haitian Agreement of 1923 was discussed between the two Governments
                    at Washington under the supervision of Department of State and that his
                    understanding is that Department approved. He adds that the 1925 agreement has
                    but slightly changed the 1923 agreement. Judge Strong<note n="36"
                        xml:id="d241fn36">Richard U. Strong, legal adviser to the High Commissioner
                        in Haiti.</note> informs me that in his opinion the agreement is in conflict
                    with the protocol of 1919 and that modifications in the protocol can only be
                    made by the United States becoming a party to the agreement and its being
                    approved by the Council of State. The protocol of 1919 was approved by the
                    Council of State in the loan law of 1922.<note n="37" xml:id="d241fn37">
                        <ref target="frus1922v02#pg_500">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1922, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 500</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In view of the above I request the Department’s instructions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Russell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
